Innovation Challenge in Ocean Plastic

This challenge from National Geographic aims to create ways to visualize plastic pollution to raise awareness. Our colleagues Gert Everaert, Jelle Rondelez, Lennert Schepers, Nick Dillen (and with help from others) developed a tool that shows how much of the microplastics would end up in the ocean if we keep on increasing the plastic production as we are currently doing.

Unfortunately it wasn’t selected as a finalist, but for sure we learn a lot and we can improve this tool for the next upcoming competition!

The app is available in http://rshiny.lifewatch.be/ng-ocean-plastic-challenge/ Give it a try!

 

Sea Invaders! - Open Sea Lab Hackaton

From the 4th to the 6th of this month took place in the Zebrastraat venue in Ghent the 2nd Open Sea Lab Hackaton. The VLIZ team “FindingDemo” starring Jonas Lescroat, Jelle Rondelez, Pieter Provoost, Ruben Perez and Salva Fernandez developed a citizen science tool to early detect the spread of invasive species. These are species which colonize habitats where they weren’t present before - more often than not due to human intervention - causing several issues such as biodiversity decrease or economical loss.

This tool was designed thinking of divers, but any person who goes to the sea could use it! You just have to select your position and the tool tells you which species could be potentially found there based on the distance to the nearest record and the environmental conditions. If you see any, you can report the sighting through the app.

They wrapped up their code in an R package, but they also made available online the beta version: Follow the link and have a look at it: https://seainvaders.eu/

 

Tracking the users of VLIZ data systems

Here at the R Code Club we are setting up a little project to estimate the impact of our data systems by looking at the citations. Who is using (and citing) our data systems? Where do they come from? From which research disciplines are they? This tool would assist in visualizing the scope of our products and services, which is specially interesting for the policy division, creating reports or applying for grants.

We are currently working in the script to scrap the citations from the web, as well as in the application. This is an app to be used by everyone interested, so we will be more than happy to hear your ideas, proposal and wishes in rcodeclub@vliz.be

 

Writing reports with R Markdown

Our colleague Cedric showed briefly how to create reports using RMarkdown. This framework allows to create documents with plain text, code outputs like plots, maps or tables or show code chunks (And not only in R! RMarkdown supports SQL, Python and other programming languages). For example, the tutorial in accessing data for the OpenSeLab II was created with RMarkdown, but also this text that you are reading! What, you can’t believe it? Just go to our GitHub repository and give yourself a try!

If you want to learn more about how to use R Markdown you will find lots of information in the official website…or simply attend our next meeting and we will show you!
